    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Digestion Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between probiotics, prebiotics, and postbiotics?</summary>
      <p>Probiotics are live microorganisms that confer health benefits when consumed in adequate amounts. Prebiotics are non-digestible fibers that feed beneficial gut bacteria, promoting their growth. Postbiotics are bioactive compounds produced by probiotic fermentation, including short-chain fatty acids and antimicrobial peptides. The most effective gut health strategy includes all three: probiotics to introduce beneficial bacteria, prebiotics to feed them, and postbiotics for their metabolic byproducts.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How many CFU do I need in a probiotic gummy?</summary>
      <p>For general digestive health, 1-10 billion CFU per day is the clinically studied range. The World Gastroenterology Organisation recommends a minimum of 1 billion CFU of a clinically studied strain. Higher CFU counts are not necessarily better — strain specificity matters more. A gummy with 1 billion CFU of LGG or BB-12 will outperform 10 billion CFU of unstudied generic strains. For spore-forming strains like Bacillus coagulans, 500 million CFU is sufficient due to near-100% acid survival.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do probiotic gummies survive stomach acid?</summary>
      <p>Survival depends on the strain. Spore-forming strains like Bacillus coagulans and Bacillus subtilis have natural acid resistance with near-100% survival rates. Non-spore-forming strains like Lactobacillus rhamnosus GG have documented but lower survival rates. Taking gummies with food provides a buffering effect that raises stomach pH and improves survival. Some products use microencapsulation or delayed-release technology to further protect non-spore-forming bacteria.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>When is the best time to take digestion gummies?</summary>
      <p>Take probiotic gummies with or immediately after a meal. Food buffers stomach acid, raising pH and improving probiotic survival. Breakfast is ideal for consistency. For prebiotic fiber gummies, take 30 minutes before a meal to slow gastric emptying and promote satiety. Consistency matters more than exact timing — take your gummy at the same time daily for best results. For the full clinical evidence on timing, read our dedicated guide on the <a href="/blog/best-time-to-take-probiotics/">best time to take probiotics</a>.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can digestion gummies help with bloating?</summary>
      <p>Yes. A 2014 systematic review in the <em>American Journal of Gastroenterology</em> found that Bifidobacterium and Lactobacillus strains significantly reduced bloating. The mechanism involves improved fermentation patterns, enhanced gut motility, and reduced visceral hypersensitivity. Temporary increased bloating during the first 1-2 weeks is common as the microbiome adjusts, followed by significant improvement.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are digestion gummies safe for daily long-term use?</summary>
      <p>Probiotic and prebiotic gummies are generally safe for daily long-term use in healthy adults. The WHO classifies probiotics as safe for general consumption. Side effects are mild and temporary (gas, bloating during first week). Individuals with severe immunocompromising conditions or central venous catheters should consult a physician, as rare probiotic-associated infections have been reported in severely immunocompromised populations.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do I need to refrigerate probiotic gummies?</summary>
      <p>Most modern probiotic gummies are shelf-stable due to microencapsulation and spore-forming strain technology. Check the product label for specific storage requirements. Shelf-stable formulations guarantee CFU counts through expiration at room temperature. Avoid storing any probiotic in hot, humid environments above 100 degrees Fahrenheit, as excessive heat can destroy live bacteria regardless of formulation.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What probiotic strains are best for digestive health?</summary>
      <p>The most clinically validated strains include: Lactobacillus rhamnosus GG (1,000+ studies, best for diarrhea prevention and general GI health), Bifidobacterium animalis BB-12 (regularity and immune modulation), Bacillus coagulans (spore-forming, acid-resistant, studied for IBS and bloating), and Bifidobacterium longum 35624 (Align's strain, studied specifically for IBS symptoms). Strain-level identification matters — generic species names are not interchangeable with specific studied strains.</p>
    </details>

